thnic migration. The contributors consider how ethnic forces have influenced political outcomes that range from voting to violence and protest mobilization to language acquisition. Conversely, each chapter demonstrates that political behavior itself has an impact on the forms and strength of ethnic identity. Thus, ethnicity is deemed to be a contested, malleable, and constructed force rather than a static characteristic inherent in the attributes of groups and individuals with a common religion, race, or national origin.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEthnic conflictzEurope, EasternvCongresses. 0aEthnic conflictzFormer Soviet republicsvCongresses. 0aPost-communismzEurope, EasternvCongresses. 0aPost-communismzFormer Soviet republicsvCongresses. 4aDiscrimination & Race Relations. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / General.2bisacsh1 aBarany, Zoltan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarany, Zoltan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBeissinger, Mark R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKymlicka, Will, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaitin, David D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoser, Robert G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoser, Robert G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPetersen, Roger D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSuny, Ronald Grigor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013